The Normal Distribution

download.file("http://www.openintro.org/stat/data/bdims.RData", destfile = "bdims.RData")
load("bdims.RData")
mdims <- subset(bdims, sex == 1)
fdims <- subset(bdims, sex == 0)

Exercise 1!

Here we see the Historgrams for the 247 men in this study an the 260 women. For both histograms we see a ver clearl bell shape. The men hgt historgram however, seems to have its information distributed much cleaner than the female hgt results.

Exercise 2!

fhgtmean <- mean(fdims$hgt)
fhgtsd   <- sd(fdims$hgt)
hist(fdims$hgt, probability = TRUE)
x <- 140:190
y <- dnorm(x = x, mean = fhgtmean, sd = fhgtsd)
lines(x = x, y = y, col = "blue")

Here we see the female hgt historgram layed below a normal distribution curve. This shows how correct the previous statement could be about the overall shape of these histograms. We can say the data follows a normal distribution

Exercise 3!

sim_norm <- rnorm(n = length(fdims$hgt), mean = fhgtmean, sd = fhgtsd)

Below we see the plot of the sim_norm value.

And here we sit it with a fit line.

qqline(sim_norm)

More of the points match up with the line when this value was used.
